{{Chembox <!-- Images --> | ImageFile = | ImageSize = | ImageAlt = <!-- Names --> | IUPACName = Palladium | OtherNames = Palladium black <!-- Sections --> | Section1 = {{Chembox Identifiers | CASNo = 7440-05-3 | PubChem = 23938 | SMILES = [Pd] | UNII = 5TWQ1V240M | EC_number = 231-115-6 | InChI = 1S/Pd | InChIKey = KDLHZDBZIXYQEI-UHFFFAOYSA-N }} | Section2 = {{Chembox Properties | Formula = Pd | MolarMass = 106.42 | Appearance = Black powder | Density = | MeltingPt = | BoilingPt = | Solubility = | SolubleOther = [[Organic Solvents]] }} | Section3 = {{Chembox Hazards | MainHazards = | FlashPt = | AutoignitionPt = }} }}
'''Palladium black''' is a coarse, [[metal sponge | sponge-like form]] of elemental [[palladium]] which offers a large [[surface area]] for [[catalyst|catalytic]] [[Activity (chemistry)|activity]]. It is used in [[organic synthesis]] as a catalyst for [[hydrogenation]] reactions.<ref name=Shigeo>{{cite book|last1=Nishimura|first1=Shigeo|title=Handbook of Heterogeneous Catalytic Hydrogenation for Organic Synthesis|date=2001|publisher=Wiley-Interscience|location=Newyork|isbn=9780471396987|pages=34-35|edition=1st|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RjZRAAAAMAAJ&q=0471396982&dq=0471396982&hl=en&sa=X&ei=BCacVMTgN5LmoASd34KQCQ&ved=0CB8Q6AEwAA}}</ref>
The term palladium black is also used colloquially to refer to a black precipitate of elemental palladium, which forms via decomposition of various palladium complexes<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Iwasawa|first=Tetsuo|last2=Tokunaga|first2=Makoto|last3=Obora|first3=Yasushi|last4=Tsuji|first4=Yasushi|date=2004-06-01|title=Homogeneous Palladium Catalyst Suppressing Pd Black Formation in Air Oxidation of Alcohols|url=https://dx.doi.org/10.1021/ja031936l|journal=Journal of the American Chemical Society|volume=126|issue=21|pages=6554–6555|doi=10.1021/ja031936l|issn=0002-7863}}</ref>.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}
==Preparation== Palladium black is typically prepared from [[palladium(II) chloride]] or [[palladium(II)-ammonium chloride]].<ref name=Shigeo /> The palladium chloride process entails the formation of [[palladium hydroxide]] using [[lithium hydroxide]] followed by [[Reducing agent|reduction]] under [[hydrogen]] gas<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Nishimura|first1=Shigeo|last2=Itaya|first2=Takashi|last3=Shiota|first3=Michio|title=Reactions of cycloalkanones in the presence of platinum-metal catalysts and hydrogen|journal=Chemical Communications (London)|date=1967|issue=9|pages=422-423|doi=10.1039/C19670000422}}</ref> while the palladium(II)-ammonium chloride route employs a solution [[formic acid]] followed by the [[Precipitation (chemistry)|precipitation]] of the catalyst using [[potassium hydroxide]].<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Zelinsky|first1=N.|last2=Glinka|first2=N.|title=Über gleichzeitige Reduktions- und Oxydationskatalyse|journal=Berichte der deutschen chemischen Gesellschaft|date=1911|volume=44|issue=3|pages=2305–2311|doi=10.1002/cber.19110440347}}</ref>
