'''Pyroligneous acid''', also called '''wood vinegar''' or '''wood acid''',<ref>[[Webster's Revised Unabridged Dictionary]] (1913)</ref> is a dark liquid produced by the [[destructive distillation]] of wood and other plant materials.

== Composition ==
The principal components of pyroligneous acid are [[acetic acid]], [[acetone]] and [[methanol]]. It was once used as a commercial source for acetic acid. In addition, the vinegar often contains 80-90% water along with some 200 [[organic compound]]s.

== History ==
Pyroligneous acid (acetum lignorum) was investigated by German chemist [[Johann Rudolph Glauber]].<ref>{{citation | author=[[Fielding H. Garrison]] | title=History of Medicine | edition=3rd | publisher=W. B. Saunders | year=1921 | page=286 | url=https://archive.org/details/3edintroductiont00garruoft}}</ref> The acid was eaten as a substitute for vinegar. It was also used topically for treating wounds, ulcers and other ailments. A [[Salt (chemistry)|salt]] can be made by [[Neutralization (chemistry)|neutralizing]] the acid with a [[lye]] made from the ashes of the burnt wood.<ref>{{citation | author=[[Johann Rudolph Glauber]] | title=Furni Novi Philosophici | volume=1 | year=1651 | publisher=Johann Jansson | pages=47–49 | url=https://archive.org/details/furninoviphiloso00glau}}</ref>

During the [[United States Civil War]] it became increasingly difficult for the [[Confederate States of America]] to obtain much needed salt. Curing meat and fish with pyroligneous acid was attempted by cooks to compensate for this deficiency. Unfortunately for the [[Confederate States Army]] it was not a comparable method of food preservation.<ref>{{cite book | title=Salt: A World History | author=[[Mark Kurlansky]] | year=2002 | publisher=Penguin Books | isbn=0-14-200161-9 | pages = 267–68}}</ref>

In the nineteenth century, pyroligneous acid was used to prepare an impure [[aluminium sulfacetate]] [[mordant]] for use with cotton, but the resulting mixture imparted a burnt odor to the cotton, and Ganswindt recommended its use be abandoned in favour of purer preparations in 1899.<ref name = Ganswindt>{{cite book|last = Ganswindt|first = Albert|title = Handbuch der Färberei und der damit verwandten vorbereitenden und vollendenden Gewerbe|year = 1889|language = German|url = http://www.deutschestextarchiv.de/book/view/ganswindt_faerberei_1889?p=296|page = 270}}</ref>

In 1895, pyroligneous acid was first marketed under the brand Wright's Liquid Smoke,<ref>{{Cite book|title=Unusual Stories of Unusual Men: Ernest H. Wright - Classification: "Condensed Smoke"|publisher=The Rotarian|year=1923|isbn=|location=|pages=209–10, 240|via=}}</ref> a [[liquid smoke]] product intended to impart the flavor and some of the preservative effects of [[Smoked meat|wood smoking]] to meats and vegetables at a time when fear about the carcinogenic effects of wood smoking was becoming prevalent.<ref name="Kraig2013">{{cite book|author=Bruce Kraig|title=The Oxford Encyclopedia of Food and Drink in America|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DOJMAgAAQBAJ&pg=RA2-PA278|date=31 January 2013|publisher=OUP USA|isbn=978-0-19-973496-2|pages=2–}}</ref>

